            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "> The \"spell\" feature is owned by Vim, so I would suggest you open this issue at vim/vim and see what happens. Whatever approach they implement, we will likely port.\n\nMakes sense. Sorry, I didn't think of that. Opened an issue with upstream.\n\n> The typical approach for that is to define :help abbreviations, e.g. https://github.com/tpope/vim-abolish\n\nIt might be a case of PEBCAK on my side, but I wasn't able to make abbreviations to do what I want \":spell in blacklist mode\" to do. I don't want to change things as I type them. I want to highlight *potential* typos and have an option to correct them.\n\nThere are cases where things that look like typos aren't typos. And there are cases where there are multiple possible ways to fix a typo (eg \"corse\" could be a typo of \"coarse\", \"core\", \"corpse\", \"course\", \"curse\", \"horse\", \"norse\" or \"worse\"). The :spell suggestion menu thing is very nice for such cases.",
